                            <div class="post-body-rich-text text-left mt-5">

                                <h2>Short on time? Here's the summary:</h2>
                            </div>
                            <br/>
                            
                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>There’s lots of talk from commentators about the impact of extremely low government bond yields and interest rates, and the fact that we are now moving into a long period of low-returns.</li>
                                <li>As an example, Commonwealth Bank’s 12-month term deposit rate in April 2021 was 0.35%, which is not even half a percent. The Consumer Price Index for 2020, which is the rate at which prices increased, was 0.9%.</li>
                                <li>To put that in perspective, if you are earning 0.35% interest and the cost of living has gone up by 0.9%, you are basically losing money and going backwards financially.</li>
                                <li>Historically, people liked term deposits and Government bonds because they are safe, but in this environment, investors should think very carefully about whether the returns from term deposits are actually delivering and meeting their financial requirements.</li>
                                <li>The good news is good income producing investments with good yields are still available. However these come with slightly more risk than a term deposit.</li>
                                <li>In this low-return environment investors can generate higher than average income returns by investing in mortgage funds.</li>
                                <li>Mortgage funds are gaining in popularity at the moment because they allow ordinary investors to invest in a fund which lends money to property owners. Those loans are secured against the property by registered mortgage. Rather than pay interest to a bank, the property owner pays interest to the fund and the fund distributes that income to its investors after it deducts its management fees. Basically, mortgage funds replace loans from banks.</li>
                                <li>Income products like mortgage funds can be used to supplement income as mortgage funds generally pay between 6% to 9% per annum, depending on the project that the fund is investing in. They also typically pay distributions every month and those distributions are usually fixed.</li>
                                <li>For those looking to supplement their income, mortgage funds are one option worth considering as investors can expect to receive a set percentage on their money every month.</li>
                                <li>However there are risks involved that mortgage fund investors should look out for. It’s important to remember that mortgage funds are not the same as term deposits. They generally lend to property owners or property developers which comes with risk. Risks can include things like a downturn in the property market, impact of natural disasters (like floods or fires), or some other impact on general economic conditions.</li>
                                <li>So if investors are considering investing in a mortgage fund, they should assess not just the quality of the fund manager offering the investment, but also the project or property that secures the loan.</li>
                                <li>Two key things investors should be aware of when considering investing in a mortgage fund:
                                <ul>
                                <li>Mortgage funds normally have a term of at least 12 months, so you need to be able to put that money aside for that period of time.</li>
                                <li>Always diversify. It’s never a good idea to put all of your investable cash into one mortgage fund. Split your investment budget between a number of different products to lower your risk. </li>
                                </ul>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                            <p>Most VentureCrowd investors seek our campaigns because they are specifically looking for higher return opportunities and that comes with a little more risk. At the end of the day, each investor’s appetite for risk is something that needs to be assessed individually – if you’re not sure, get independent financial advice to help you create a structured investment plan for your needs and help identify investments that fit into that plan.</p>
                               
                                

